  <h2>Why Solo</h2>

  <p>
    Solo sailing isn't about proving you're tough. It's about proving your systems work when there's no one to bail you out. That's why I did two days alone on the Saint John River — not for the Instagram story, but because when you're preparing for offshore racing, you need to know that your boat, your gear, and your own decision-making hold up without a crew to lean on.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Saint John River is a good testing ground. It's sheltered enough that a mistake won't kill you, but it has enough current, tidal influence, and variable wind to keep you honest. The Reversing Falls section alone demands respect — the tidal bore where the Bay of Fundy forces the river to reverse direction is something you time carefully or not at all.
  </p>

  <h2>Day One: Everything Works Until It Doesn't</h2>

  <p>
    I launched early morning with light winds out of the southwest. The plan was simple: sail downriver, anchor for the night, sail back the next day. A shakedown. A systems check.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first few hours were textbook. Good wind, clean tacks, the autopilot handled the straight sections while I checked rigging and tuned sail trim. By early afternoon the wind picked up — 15 knots gusting to 20 — and I was in my groove.
  </p>

  <p>
    Then a block failed. One of the jib sheet blocks popped its shackle pin and the whole assembly came free. Suddenly my headsail was flogging, the sheet was loose, and I was trying to wrestle it under control single-handed in building wind.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the solo sailing test. No one to take the helm while you fix it. No one to grab the loose line while you dig through the parts bag. You deal with it or you don't. I got the sail down, rigged a temporary block using a carabiner and some spare line, and got sailing again within twenty minutes. Not elegant, but functional.
  </p>

  <h2>The Night Anchor</h2>

  <p>
    I anchored in a quiet cove as the sun went down. Made dinner on the camp stove, checked the anchor twice, and sat in the cockpit watching the river go dark. There's a specific kind of quiet that happens on a boat at anchor alone. No engine, no traffic, just water against the hull and the occasional splash of something alive underneath you.
  </p>

  <p>
    I ran through my gear mentally. The block failure was a wake-up call. The shackle pin had worn thin — something I should have caught during the pre-trip inspection. I made a note: print replacement shackle pins in PA-CF as spares. Stronger than the brass ones, lighter, and I can make them any dimension I need.
  </p>

  <h2>Day Two: Coming Back Against the Current</h2>

  <p>
    The return trip was harder. Wind had shifted to the north, which meant beating upriver against both wind and current. Short tacks, constant attention, no breaks. Solo sailing upwind is physically demanding — every tack means crossing the cockpit, releasing one sheet, grinding in the other, adjusting course, checking for traffic, and doing it all again five minutes later.
  </p>

  <p>
    By mid-afternoon I was tired in a way that desk work never produces. The good kind of tired — the kind where every muscle did something useful. I made the dock by late afternoon, tied up, and sat on the foredeck for a while.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Proved</h2>

  <p>
    The trip confirmed a few things I needed to know:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>The boat is solid.</strong> Hull, rigging, engine, electrical — everything performed. One hardware failure in two days is acceptable if you catch the wear patterns early</li>
    <li><strong>The 3D-printed parts held up.</strong> Several components on board were printed — cleat spacers, instrument mount, tiller extension adapter. All fine after two days of real use</li>
    <li><strong>Solo protocols work.</strong> My routines for sail changes, anchoring, and emergency response are sound. They need to be faster, but the sequences are right</li>
    <li><strong>I need a better spares kit.</strong> The block failure could have ended the trip if I hadn't improvised. A dedicated kit of 3D-printed replacement hardware goes on the permanent packing list</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The 3D3D Angle</h2>

  <p>
    Every trip like this feeds back into the work at 3D3D. I come home with a list of parts that need to be designed, redesigned, or added to the inventory. The shackle pin. A better fairlead for the jib sheet. A mounting bracket for the handheld VHF that doesn't require drilling into the bulkhead.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sailing is one of the best testing environments for 3D-printed parts because the conditions are real and the feedback is immediate. A part either works on the water or it doesn't. There's no simulation that replicates the combination of salt, UV, vibration, and shock loading that a sailboat delivers every single day.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two days solo isn't an ocean crossing. But it's proof of concept — for the boat, for the parts, and for the person. All three passed.
  </p>
